In TypeScript, you can use the `readonly` keyword to assert that a property or a type will only have a single value during the entire runtime of your program. This is useful when you know that a value will only have one specific type, but TypeScript doesn't know that for sure.

Here's an example:

```typescript
interface MyType {
  value1: string;
  value2: number;
  value3: boolean;
}

const myValue: MyType = {
  value1: 'hello',
  value2: 42,
  value3: true,
};

// You can assert that the value of 'value1' is always a string here
// because you know that in practice it will never be anything else.
// This tells TypeScript that the 'value1' property can only have the 'string' type.
const value1: string = myValue.value1;
```

In this example, you can see that we have an interface `MyType` that has three properties: `value1`, `value2`, and `value3`. We then create an instance of this interface with some values. We know that `value1` will always be a string, so we can use the `readonly` keyword to assert that it will only have the `string` type. This tells TypeScript that we know the type of `value1` and it won't be any other type, even though TypeScript itself doesn't have enough information to infer it.

You can also use this technique with generic types, like this:

```typescript
interface MyType<T> {
  value1: T;
}

